

Antibodies are proteins found in the body that are produced by the immune system to fight off foreign invaders like bacteria, viruses, and toxins. They are also known as immunoglobulins, and they help protect the body from disease. Antibodies recognize and bind to specific molecules called antigens, which can be found on the surface of bacteria, viruses, and other foreign invaders. This binding triggers a cascade of events that leads to the destruction of the invading organism.

Antibodies are produced by B-cells, which are a type of white blood cell. When a B-cell encounters an antigen, it will produce an antibody specific to that antigen. This process is known as clonal selection, and it allows the B-cell to recognize and bind to the antigen. Once the antibody binds to the antigen, it will activate other parts of the immune system, such as macrophages, to help destroy the invading organism.

The structure of antibodies is complex and consists of two heavy chains and two light chains. Each chain has a variable region, which is responsible for recognizing and binding to the antigen, and a constant region, which is responsible for activating the immune system. Antibodies can also be divided into five classes based on the structure of their heavy chains: IgG, IgM, IgA, IgD, and IgE. Each class of antibody has a specific role in the immune response.

IgG is the most common type of antibody and is responsible for fighting off bacterial and viral infections. IgM is the first type of antibody to be produced in response to an infection, and it helps to activate the immune system. IgA is found in mucosal secretions, such as saliva and tears, and helps to protect the body from infection at these sites. IgD is found on the surface of B-cells and helps to activate them. IgE is involved in allergic reactions and helps to protect the body from parasites.

